146-148 are repeated in three other Books‚ near the beginning of each (ii 59, iii 91, vi 39). Any of these passages will show that Lucr. did not write the lines sor Book i, but inserted them here as an after-thought. For elsewhere he begins by comparing mankind to children srightened by the dark, so that the mention of the sun, relevant there, is not really relevant here.

This is important, as a clear case os a practice which is probably common throughout the poem: see Index under ‘insertions.‘
